      <h2>Choosing Boots by Trade</h2>
      <p>Different trades put different demands on footwear. Here's a quick cheat sheet:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>General Construction / Framing:</strong> Need steel or composite toe, slip resistance, and puncture protection. Look for NINGO Steel Toe or NORTIV 8 Waterproof Steel Toe.</li>
        <li><strong>Concrete / Masonry:</strong> Waterproof is non-negotiable. Alkaline in concrete slurry can burn skin and damage leather. NORTIV 8 Waterproof or NINGO Composite Toe with waterproofing.</li>
        <li><strong>Roofing:</strong> Slip resistance is priority #1. Lightweight boots for climbing. Furuian Steel Toe or NORTIV 8 TROOP.</li>
        <li><strong>Electrical / Low Voltage:</strong> EH-rated boots required. NINGO Steel Toe has EH protection. Composite toe also preferred as it doesn't conduct electricity.</li>
        <li><strong>HVAC / Mechanical:</strong> Comfort for all-day standing and walking on hard surfaces. Waterproof soft toe boots or lightweight steel toe.</li>
        <li><strong>Demolition / Heavy Civil:</strong> Maximum protection. Heavy-duty steel toe, puncture-resistant sole, full-grain leather upper. Heavy Duty Steel Toe Leather Boots are ideal.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Budget Considerations</h2>
      <p>You don't need to spend $300 to get a solid pair of work boots. Many options in the $50–$120 range deliver excellent protection and comfort. The key is knowing what to prioritize at each price point:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Under $80:</strong> Look for steel toe, slip resistance, and basic comfort. Furuian Steel Toe Boots and NORTIV 8 TROOP fit this bracket.</li>
        <li><strong>$80–$130:</strong> Expect better materials, actual waterproofing, and composite toe options. NINGO Steel Toe, NORTIV 8 Waterproof.</li>
        <li><strong>$130+:</strong> Premium leather, advanced cushioning, alloy toe options, and longer warranties.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Final Tips Before You Buy</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Break them in gradually.</strong> Wear new boots for 2–4 hours the first day, then increase. Don't take them straight to a 12-hour shift.</li>
        <li><strong>Buy two pairs if you work daily.</strong> Rotating boots lets each pair dry out fully, extending lifespan by 50% or more.</li>
        <li><strong>Replace insoles every 3–4 months.</strong> Even if the boots look fine, the cushioning degrades. A $15 insole replacement can make $100 boots feel like $200 boots.</li>
        <li><strong>Waterproof regularly.</strong> Leather needs conditioning and waterproofing every 2–3 months. Mink oil, beeswax, or silicone spray all work — choose based on your climate.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Your work boots are the foundation of your safety and comfort on the job. Invest the time to choose wisely, maintain them properly, and your feet — and your back — will thank you for years to come.</p>

